 :tx/rationale "GENESIS-2: THE CONCEPT AS MISSING PRIMITIVE. Knowledge emerges through CONCEPT CRYSTALLIZATION — not through keyword matching, not through structured flags, not through extractors. A concept is a first-class entity in the store that represents a cluster of meaning, evolves over time, and connects observations through shared conceptual membership. Concepts are: (1) EMERGENT — they arise when the system detects multiple observations cluster in embedding space. Not predefined by taxonomy. (2) MUTABLE — via retract-then-assert. As observations accumulate, description and embedding update. Concepts split when internal variance exceeds threshold, merge when centroids converge. (3) BRIDGES ACROSS AGENTS — new agents inherit concepts, not raw observations. The seed shows 'Known concepts: event-sourcing (7 obs), error-suppression (6 obs)' — a conceptual vocabulary, not a data dump. (4) SOLVE SYNONYMY — two agents use different tags for same pattern; concept embeddings detect semantic proximity and propose merge. (5) EVOLVE WITH THE GRAPH — each new observation updates concept membership and centroid. The concept graph IS the knowledge structure. Formal definition: a concept is an entity with (:concept/name String One), (:concept/description String One), (:concept/embedding Bytes One — centroid of member embeddings), (:concept/member-count Long One), (:concept/created-at Long One). Observations link via (:exploration/concept Ref Many). This implements OBSERVER-6 (Ontology Discovery) from the bedrock vision: 'observation clustering → proposed categories.'"
